<!--
Feedback memories hold guidance the operator has given: what to keep doing, what to stop
doing. Record both corrections AND confirmations — if Claude only saves corrections, it
drifts away from approaches the operator has already validated.

Structure each feedback entry as:

  <rule>

  **Why:** <reason — often a past incident or strong preference>

  **How to apply:** <when/where this kicks in>

Examples:

---
Integration tests must hit a real database, not mocks.

**Why:** Previous project had mocked tests pass while a prod migration failed silently.
Divergence went undetected for weeks.

**How to apply:** For any test that touches the data layer — unit tests of pure logic
can still use test doubles, but the moment a DB query is involved, use testcontainers
or a real local Postgres.
---

Keep responses terse — no trailing "I just did X" summaries; the diff is visible.

**Why:** Operator reads diffs directly and finds recap paragraphs noise.

**How to apply:** End-of-turn summaries at most one sentence. No bullet lists recapping
what already shipped.
---
-->

